  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Positive vs Normative Economics</h2>
    <p>A key distinction in economics is between statements that describe the world as it is versus statements about how it should be.</p>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="content-card">
        <div class="content-card-title">Positive economics</div>
        <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">Objective, factual statements that can be tested against empirical evidence. They describe cause-and-effect relationships.</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-muted); margin-top:0.5rem;">Example: "A 10% increase in the minimum wage leads to a 2% reduction in employment."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <div class="content-card-title">Normative economics</div>
        <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">Subjective statements based on value judgements — they cannot be proven right or wrong by evidence alone.</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-muted); margin-top:0.5rem;">Example: "The government should raise the minimum wage to reduce poverty."</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout exam-tip">
      <div class="callout-title">Exam tip</div>
      <p>In exams you may be asked to identify whether a statement is positive or normative. Look for value-laden words like "should", "ought to", "fair", or "better" — these signal normative statements. Positive statements can, in principle, be tested with data.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Equity and Equality</h3>
    <p><strong>Equality</strong> means everyone receives the same share. <strong>Equity</strong> means fairness — which may or may not involve equal distribution. What counts as equitable is a normative judgement.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Economic Methodology</h2>
    <p>Economics uses a scientific method adapted for social phenomena:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Logic</strong> — deductive reasoning from assumptions to conclusions</li>
      <li><strong>Hypotheses</strong> — testable predictions about economic relationships</li>
      <li><strong>Models</strong> — simplified representations of reality that isolate key variables</li>
      <li><strong>Ceteris paribus</strong> — "all other things being equal" — a key assumption that allows economists to study the effect of one variable while holding all others constant</li>
      <li><strong>Empirical evidence</strong> — data collected from the real world to test hypotheses</li>
      <li><strong>Refutation</strong> — when evidence consistently contradicts a theory, the theory must be revised or abandoned</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout key-term">
      <div class="callout-title">Key term</div>
      <p><strong>Ceteris paribus:</strong> A Latin phrase meaning "all other things being equal." Used to isolate the effect of one variable by assuming all other relevant variables remain unchanged. For example, when analysing the effect of price on quantity demanded, we assume income and tastes do not change.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">History of Economic Thought</h2>

    <h3>18th Century: Adam Smith and Laissez-Faire</h3>
    <p>Adam Smith (1776, <em>The Wealth of Nations</em>) argued that free markets, guided by the "invisible hand" of self-interest and competition, efficiently allocate resources without central direction. This laid the foundation for <strong>classical economics</strong> and the case for laissez-faire (minimal government intervention).</p>

    <h3>19th Century: Classical and Marxist Economics</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Classical microeconomics</strong> developed the concept of <em>utility</em> (satisfaction from consumption) and the idea of the <em>margin</em> (decisions based on the additional cost or benefit of the next unit)</li>
      <li><strong>Classical macroeconomics (Say's Law)</strong> — supply creates its own demand; the economy will naturally return to full employment</li>
      <li><strong>Marxist critique</strong> — Karl Marx challenged capitalism, arguing it exploited workers and was inherently unstable</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>20th Century: Keynesian Revolution and Counter-Revolution</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Keynesian economics</strong> (John Maynard Keynes, 1936) — markets can get stuck in recessions; active government intervention (fiscal and monetary policy) is needed to stabilise the economy and restore full employment</li>
      <li><strong>Rise of macroeconomic policy</strong> — governments began actively managing the economy</li>
      <li><strong>Monetarist/new classical counter-revolution</strong> — economists like Milton Friedman argued that government intervention often makes things worse; the economy has natural self-correcting mechanisms and markets should be trusted</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>21st Century: Behavioural Economics and Sustainability</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Behavioural economics</strong> — draws on psychology to challenge the assumption of rational decision-making; recognises that people are subject to biases, emotions, and limited information</li>
      <li><strong>Interdependencies</strong> — growing awareness of the connections between the economy, society, and the natural environment</li>
      <li><strong>Circular economy</strong> — a model focused on reducing waste, reusing resources, and designing for sustainability rather than linear "take-make-dispose" production</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Positive statements are testable facts; normative statements are value judgements</li>
      <li>Ceteris paribus isolates the effect of one variable</li>
      <li>Economic models simplify reality to highlight key relationships</li>
      <li>Adam Smith: free markets and the invisible hand (18th c.)</li>
      <li>Keynes: government intervention needed to fix recessions (20th c.)</li>
      <li>Monetarists: markets self-correct; distrust intervention (20th c.)</li>
      <li>Behavioural economics: people are not perfectly rational</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

