  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions</div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. Classify each of the following statements as positive or normative. Explain your reasoning.
        <ul style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
          <li>a) "Raising income tax rates reduces disposable income."</li>
          <li>b) "The government should reduce income inequality."</li>
          <li>c) "A carbon tax would reduce greenhouse gas emissions."</li>
          <li>d) "Free trade is unfair to workers in developing countries."</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          <ul>
            <li>a) <strong>Positive</strong> — a factual, testable claim about the effect of tax changes on income</li>
            <li>b) <strong>Normative</strong> — "should" signals a value judgement; the desirability of reducing inequality is debatable</li>
            <li>c) <strong>Positive</strong> — an empirically testable cause-and-effect claim</li>
            <li>d) <strong>Normative</strong> — "unfair" is a value-laden term; this is a judgement, not a fact</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. Explain what is meant by "ceteris paribus" and why it is important in economic analysis.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          Ceteris paribus means "all other things being equal." It is used to isolate the relationship between two variables by assuming all other relevant factors remain constant. This is essential in economics because many variables change simultaneously in the real world. For example, when analysing how a price increase affects demand, ceteris paribus assumes income, tastes, and prices of related goods do not change — otherwise it would be impossible to determine which factor caused the change in quantity demanded.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">3. Briefly outline how Keynesian economics differed from the classical view of the economy.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          Classical economists believed markets were self-correcting: if the economy fell into recession, wages and prices would fall, restoring full employment automatically (Say's Law). Keynes challenged this during the Great Depression, arguing that demand could be persistently low, leading to long-lasting unemployment. He advocated for active government intervention — increasing spending or cutting taxes — to boost aggregate demand and restore full employment. Unlike classical economists, Keynes did not trust the market to self-correct quickly or reliably.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">4. Explain how behavioural economics challenges the assumption of rational consumer choice.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          Traditional economics assumes consumers act rationally — they have perfect information, consistent preferences, and always maximise their utility. Behavioural economics, drawing on psychology, shows this is not always true. People are subject to cognitive biases (e.g., anchoring, availability bias), have bounded rationality (limited information and processing capacity), limited self-control, and are not purely self-interested. These insights have practical applications in policy — for example, "nudging" people toward better choices by changing how options are presented (choice architecture).
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

